<subSubSection id="C2455BA07607EC083F3CB48ABBA4B18A" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="1BE181569604D6967DF2BFD15EB8DD7E" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D71F54350042194EAA1DDAC5972E00B2" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Legs. Tibiae flattened and broadened apically (Figs 78, 80), apparently for digging, tarsi without apically extending lobes or pads, tarsal claws with 2-3 apices per side. Also, posterior edge of pronotum bidentate mesally; anterior edge of scutellum straight, females with compound eyes nearly flat and antennae reaching only 2/3 of distance to pronotal hind angles; bursa copulatrix with proximal (only) sclerites parallel sided (Fig. 30). Known from: Brazil, Bolivia, 3 spp.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
